# 6. Target System Design (Reference Architecture)

## 6.1 Architecture principles

- **Order-native, standards-aligned. **Model the Order as the primary record from day one; align to NDC and ONE Order. Maintain PNR/e-ticket compatibility as an explicit bridging layer, not as the core.

- **API-first and modular. **Every capability is a service behind a well-defined API. Modules must be independently deployable and independently sellable.

- **Cloud-native. **Containerised microservices, horizontal scalability, infrastructure-as-code, multi-AZ by default.

- **Event-driven core. **An event/streaming backbone for state changes (orders, inventory, ops) enables real-time analytics, audit, and loose coupling.

- **Resilience and data integrity above all. **Graceful degradation, idempotency, no single points of failure, strong consistency where money and seats are concerned.

- **Coexistence by design. **Assume the platform will run alongside legacy systems for years; bridging and synchronisation are core features, not migration scripts.

## 6.2 Logical layers

A workable layering of the platform:

- **Experience layer — **web IBE, mobile, kiosk, agent and airport apps; consume the same offer/order APIs.

- **Channel ****&**** distribution layer — **API gateway, NDC endpoints, GDS adapters, partner/OTA connectors, BFF services per channel.

- **Retailing layer — **offer management, pricing/optimisation, ancillaries/merchandising, personalisation.

- **Order ****&**** fulfilment layer — **order management, servicing, ticketing/EMD bridge, delivery/DCS, baggage, load control.

- **Core services layer — **inventory/availability, schedules, fares, payments & settlement, revenue accounting integration.

- **Data ****&**** intelligence layer — **streaming backbone, data lake/warehouse, customer data platform, ML/AI feature and model services.

- **Platform layer — **identity & access, secrets, observability, configuration/feature flags, audit, CI/CD.

## 6.3 Technology & integration choices (illustrative, to be ratified)

| **Concern** | **Indicative approach** |
| --- | --- |
| Compute / deployment | Containers + orchestration (Kubernetes), infra-as-code, multi-region/multi-AZ |
| Service communication | REST/JSON + async events; gRPC for high-throughput internal paths |
| Messaging / streaming | Durable event log (e.g. Kafka-class) for order/inventory/ops events |
| Data stores | Polyglot: strongly-consistent store for orders/inventory; document store for offers; analytics warehouse + lake |
| Standards / schemas | IATA NDC (current schema generation), ONE Order, EDIFACT/Type-B adapters for legacy interop |
| APIs | OpenAPI-documented gateway; NDC-conformant external endpoints; partner sandbox |
| AI / pricing | Pluggable optimisation services; option to integrate best-of-breed dynamic-pricing engines |
| Security | Zero-trust, encryption in transit and at rest, tokenised payments (PCI DSS scope isolation) |

*Technology choices are deliberately indicative — they are decisions for the architecture board, recorded here to frame the trade-offs.*

# 7. Non-Functional Requirements

For a PSS the non-functional requirements are the product. The following are the dimensions that must carry explicit, testable targets before build:

| **Dimension** | **Requirement direction** |
| --- | --- |
| **Availability** | Core booking, check-in and DCS paths must target very high availability with graceful degradation; no single point of failure; tested failover. Outages translate directly into grounded flights. |
| **Performance** | Sub-second shopping/availability responses at high look-to-book ratios; offer generation at scale; predictable latency under peak (holiday, IROPS surges). |
| **Scalability** | Horizontal scale to traffic spikes; multi-tenant if serving multiple carriers; isolate noisy neighbours. |
| **Data integrity** | Exactly-once financial and seat transactions; idempotency; strong consistency for inventory and orders; full auditability. |
| **Security** | PCI DSS for payments; strong auth/authorisation; encryption everywhere; secrets management; intrusion detection. |
| **Privacy ****&**** compliance** | GDPR and regional data-protection; passenger data residency; consent management; API/PNR data-sharing (e.g. API/PNR government requirements) handled correctly. |
| **Observability** | End-to-end tracing, business and technical metrics, alerting, and replayable event history. |
| **Recoverability** | Defined RPO/RTO; backups; disaster-recovery runbooks rehearsed, not just documented. |
| **Interoperability** | Clean coexistence with legacy PSS, GDS and partner systems via standards-based adapters. |

# 8. Build, Buy or Partner

Not every component should be built. The capability map (5.6) and the market structure (3) point to a deliberate sourcing strategy:

- **Build the differentiators: **order management, offer assembly, inventory/availability, and the API/distribution core — these define the platform and should be owned.

- **Integrate or partner for specialised/regulated capabilities: **dynamic-pricing engines, weight-and-balance/load control (often certified third parties), payment orchestration, and potentially revenue management and loyalty — areas where best-of-breed specialists already exist.

- **Bridge, don****'****t rebuild, the legacy: **treat PNR/e-ticket/EMD compatibility as adapters (mirroring the "PSS Sync"-style bridges incumbents ship) so the platform can coexist and migrate carriers incrementally.

This sourcing posture also defines the realistic commercial entry point: the platform can be sold as a full suite to greenfield carriers (the Riyadh-Air-style "start clean on Offer & Order" pattern) or as individual modules into established carriers running multi-vendor strategies.

# 9. Implementation Roadmap

The roadmap is phased to deliver value early and de-risk continuously. Durations are indicative placeholders for planning, not commitments; each phase ends with a usable, sellable increment. Industry experience suggests full transformation programmes run multi-year — this plan front-loads a revenue-generating core and treats the move to fully native Offer & Order as an explicit later phase.

| **Phase** | **Focus** | **Key deliverables** | **Indicative window** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| **Phase 0 — Discovery ****&**** foundations** | De-risk and set foundations | Architecture decisions ratified; standards baseline (NDC/ONE Order); platform layer (CI/CD, IAM, observability); domain model for Order; test/simulation harness. | 0–3 mo |
| **Phase 1 — Core MVP** | Sell a flight | Order management (order-native + PNR bridge), inventory/availability, filed-fare pricing, direct IBE/mobile, payments, e-ticket/EMD bridge. A carrier can shop, book, pay. | 3–9 mo |
| **Phase 2 — Retailing ****&**** distribution** | Sell more, everywhere | Offer management, ancillaries/merchandising, NDC distribution (OTA/TMC), B2B agent portal, Corporate & SME booking, FFP/loyalty, WhatsApp conversational commerce, reporting & BI, GDS adapters. | 9–18 mo |
| **Phase 3 — Delivery ****&**** operations** | Fly the passenger | DCS (check-in, seating, boarding), baggage, IROPS/disruption, weight-and-balance, Cargo (CMS) integration, settlement & revenue-accounting integration. | 15–24 mo |
| **Phase 4 — Native Offer ****&**** Order + AI** | Lead, don't follow | Full ONE Order native fulfilment, dynamic/continuous pricing, AI personalisation, settlement-with-orders, order-based interline; retire legacy bridges per carrier. | 24–42 mo |

*Phases overlap deliberately; windows are planning placeholders to be replaced with estimated effort once scope is fixed.*

## 9.1 Sequencing logic

- Ship a revenue surface (Phase 1) before breadth — a carrier should be able to sell a ticket on the platform as early as possible.

- Defer the hardest operationally-critical, safety-adjacent pieces (DCS, weight & balance) until the commercial core is proven and stable.

- Keep the legacy bridge alive throughout so adoption never requires a big-bang cutover.

- Treat full native Offer & Order as a destination reached incrementally, not a prerequisite for launch.

# 10. Risks and Mitigations

PSS programmes are high-stakes: a PSS is effectively a transplant of an airline's vital systems, and migrations carry hundreds of catalogued risk types. Incumbent migration practices stress structured, multi-stage testing (component through end-to-end business-process), dress rehearsals, parallel running and disciplined cutover with on-the-ground post-go-live support. The table below captures the principal risks and the design/process responses.

| **Risk** | **Mitigation** |
| --- | --- |
| Operational disruption (downtime, glitches grounding flights) | High-availability design, graceful degradation, parallel running, rehearsed cutover, dedicated post-go-live support window. |
| Data migration errors / loss (future bookings, history, preferences) | Rigorous data mapping and reconciliation, dual-run validation, rollback plan, bridge that keeps legacy authoritative until proven. |
| Distribution continuity (e.g. losing GDS/channel access mid-transition) | Maintain GDS/NDC adapters and dual distribution through transition; contractual continuity with channels. |
| Underestimated scope & cost (multi-year, tens of millions per carrier) | Phased delivery with value at each stage; explicit scope gates; reuse partners for non-differentiators. |
| Codeshare / interline / partner breakage | Standards conformance (NDC, ONE Order, Future of Interline); partner test environments; staged enablement. |
| Organisational misalignment / silos | Cross-functional governance forums; clear ownership; commercial + IT + ops aligned from Phase 0. |
| Vendor / standards drift (schema versions evolve) | Track IATA schema generations; abstract standards behind adapters; automated conformance testing. |
| Big-bang temptation | Architecturally enforce modularity and coexistence so incremental adoption is always the cheaper path. |

# 11. Open Questions for the Team

These decisions materially shape scope, cost and architecture and should be resolved before detailed design:

- Target customer: greenfield/new carriers (start clean on Offer & Order), established carriers migrating, or a module strategy into multi-vendor estates? This drives everything below.

- Carrier type focus: full-service, low-cost, hybrid, or multi-tenant across types? (LCC vs FSC priorities differ sharply on ancillaries, interline and complexity.)

- Full-suite vs best-of-breed modules: which capabilities do we commit to building vs integrating/partnering (see Section 8)?

- Geography & compliance footprint: which regions first, and therefore which data-residency, payment and government-data regimes apply?

- Migration posture: are we offering a managed migration/coexistence service, or a clean-start platform only?

- AI/dynamic pricing: build, buy or partner — and how central is it to the value proposition?

- Commercial model: licence, SaaS subscription, transaction-based, or hybrid?

# 12. Appendix

## 12.1 Glossary

| **Term** | **Meaning** |
| --- | --- |
| PSS | Passenger Service System — the airline's reservation, inventory and departure-control core. |
| CRS | Central Reservation System — schedules, fares, bookings, PNRs. |
| ICS / AIS | Inventory (Control) System — sellable seats by flight and class. |
| DCS | Departure Control System — check-in, boarding, baggage, load control. |
| PNR | Passenger Name Record — legacy booking record. |
| EMD | Electronic Miscellaneous Document — issuance for ancillaries/services. |
| RBD | Reservation Booking Designator — booking class/fare bucket. |
| NDC | New Distribution Capability — IATA Offer/Order distribution data standard. |
| ONE Order | IATA standard consolidating PNR/e-ticket/EMD into a single Order record. |
| OOSD | Offer, Order, Settle, Deliver — the modern-retailing framework. |
| MAR | Modern Airline Retailing — IATA programme toward 100% Offers and Orders. |
| GDS | Global Distribution System — intermediary distribution networks (e.g. Amadeus, Sabre, Travelport). |
| IBE | Internet Booking Engine — the airline's direct online sales surface. |
| FFP | Frequent Flyer Program — the airline's loyalty programme. |
| CMS | Cargo Management System — dedicated cargo platform, integrated with the PSS. |
| AWB | Air Waybill — the cargo equivalent of a ticket/contract of carriage. |
| OTA / TMC | Online Travel Agency / Travel Management Company — indirect sales intermediaries. |
| IROPS | Irregular Operations — disruption handling and re-accommodation. |

## 12.2 Primary sources consulted

This document synthesises publicly available material (June 2026), including IATA programme pages on Modern Airline Retailing, NDC and ONE Order; vendor materials for Amadeus Nevio, Sabre SabreMosaic, Accelya FLX ONE and Hitit Oxygen; PSS market analyses; and industry commentary on migration practice. Specific figures (market size, adoption rates, investment ranges) vary by source and should be re-validated before being used in any business case.

